# Memory Bible Rule

Treat `.cursor/memory/README.md` and all files in `.cursor/memory/` as the project source of truth ("bible") for architecture, modules, flows, and API behavior.

## Mandatory behavior

- Before substantial implementation, consult relevant docs in `.cursor/memory/`.
- Align code changes with the documented architecture and module boundaries.
- If code changes alter behavior, APIs, flows, or structure, update the corresponding `.cursor/memory/*.md` docs in the same task.
- If a new feature/module/pattern is introduced, add or extend docs in `.cursor/memory/` and link it from `.cursor/memory/README.md`.
- Do not consider a feature/refactor complete until documentation is updated.

## Minimum doc updates required when applicable

- Architecture changes -> `01-architecture-overview.md` and/or `02-frontend-structure.md`
- New/changed API contracts -> `03-api-client.md` and `15-api-endpoint-mapping.md`
- Data model changes -> `04-type-system.md`
- Auth/permission changes -> `05-authentication-permissions.md`
- Module behavior changes -> corresponding `06-12` module docs
- Cross-module flow changes -> `14-module-relationships.md`
- New reusable UI conventions -> `13-component-patterns.md`

## Quality bar

- Keep docs accurate, concise, and immediately actionable for future agents.
- Prefer updating existing memory docs over creating duplicate files.
